# Epic 3: Data Pre-processing

## Introduction

Data preprocessing is a crucial step in the OptiCrop Smart Agricultural Production Optimization System. It prepares the collected agricultural dataset for machine learning by improving data quality and ensuring consistency. Proper preprocessing helps increase the accuracy and reliability of crop prediction models.

## Dataset Loading

The agricultural dataset was imported into the Python environment using the Pandas library. The dataset contains soil and environmental parameters including Nitrogen (N), Phosphorous (P), Potassium (K), temperature, humidity, pH, rainfall, and crop labels.

## Dataset Inspection

The dataset was examined to understand its structure, dimensions, column names, and data types. Functions such as `head()`, `shape()`, and `info()` were used to verify the dataset before preprocessing.

## Missing Value Analysis

The dataset was checked for missing or null values using the `isnull().sum()` function. No missing values were found, indicating that the dataset was complete and suitable for further analysis.

## Duplicate Record Handling

The dataset was analyzed for duplicate records using the `duplicated()` function. If duplicates were present, they were removed to avoid bias during model training and improve prediction accuracy.

## Data Type Verification

Each attribute was verified to ensure it had the appropriate data type. Numerical features such as Nitrogen, Phosphorous, Potassium, temperature, humidity, pH, and rainfall were confirmed to be numeric, while the crop label was identified as a categorical attribute.

## Label Encoding

Since machine learning algorithms require numerical values, the crop labels were converted into numeric form using the Label Encoder from the Scikit-learn library. This transformation allows the model to process the target variable efficiently.

## Feature and Target Separation

The dataset was divided into input features and the target variable. Soil and environmental parameters were selected as input features, while the encoded crop label was used as the target for prediction.

## Train-Test Split

The processed dataset was divided into training and testing sets using an 80:20 ratio. The training set is used to build the machine learning model, while the testing set is used to evaluate its performance on unseen data.

## Processed Dataset

After completing all preprocessing steps, the cleaned and transformed dataset was saved as a processed dataset. This dataset serves as the input for the machine learning algorithms used in the next phase of the project.

## Conclusion

The data preprocessing phase ensured that the dataset was clean, structured, and suitable for machine learning. By performing dataset inspection, missing value analysis, duplicate removal, label encoding, feature selection, and train-test splitting, the data was successfully prepared for building accurate crop prediction models.
